Does not respect GTK4 system-wide dark-mode preference

note.body:
According to the discussion on the https://discourse.gnome.org/t/file-roller-not-respecting-gtk4-system-wide-dark-mode-preference/24859/2:
> Applications using libadwaita should use the appropriate API instead of using GtkSettings; additionally, libadwaita only uses the Settings xdg-desktop-portal to query the style to be used (light/dark, high contrast, or the accent colors). You need to ensure you’re starting the desktop portal in your session, and that you configured it correctly to start a portal implementation that supports the Settings interface. You should ask on a user support forum for Sway.

I've asked to the Sway folks (on IRC) and they told me they're not going to implement the Settings XDG portal interface, I don't know why, I don't have enough context to understand.

So, yes, I'm going to close this as likely not Gnome-related.

Thanks for helping me diagnose the issue.

Hi, I was redirected here from this [forum thread](https://discourse.gnome.org/t/compatibility-with-winrar-archives/24861).

I am using file-roller 44.3 (Debian/testing trixie package) and libarchive 3.7.4 and I suspect I am experiencing a variant of this issue with this old RAR file:
```
$ file IndexLSD.rar 
IndexLSD.rar: RAR archive data, v4, os: Win32
```

I can decompress this file if:

If I have only `unrar-free` installed, file-roller isn't able to decompress the file and shows a popup "Extraction not performed".

Please find attached the sample file. It's safe, it's a MS Word document of 24 years ago (!). It's MD5 checksum is `336b81108c720115af4671ff9121cd66`.

note.body:
Such is better asked on https://discourse.gnome.org/ I think.

GNOME Shell has a global dark style setting. That sets color-scheme to prefer-dark, you have it set to default. Try manually setting it with:
```
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme "prefer-dark"
```

Hi @scaforchio, thanks for taking the time to report this. Please always provide the exact version of the application and distribution/operating system information when reporting an issue. Thanks!

Without a good stack trace from the crash it is very hard to find out why the crash happens. Can you please get us a stack trace which includes debug symbols? Please see https://handbook.gnome.org/issues/stack-traces.html for more information and also make sure it includes debug symbols.

**Only** if you do not have `systemd-coredump` installed on your system, instead follow https://wiki.gnome.org/GettingInTouch/Bugzilla/GettingTraces how to use `gdb` and also do make sure to install or compile debug symbols for the crashing application and the libraries used by it. In case you use Arch Linux, see https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Debug_-_Getting_Traces
